In a couple of places, a wstring is passed as an argument to std::fstream, like so:

```
void f(const Path& path)
{
      std::fstream stream;
      stream.open(path.toWString().c_str());
      [...]
}
```

This doesn't work on Linux, where paths are strings of `char`, not `wchar_t`. Hence my question: is it possible / a good idea to use non-wide strings for paths on Windows ? Or should we rather use `#ifdef` to discriminate between Windows and others?
